{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510601"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:32:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:32:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11627"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11627"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.31,0.06,0.33,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4254"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112339"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4254"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-03-15T19:51:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T08:52:00+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-05-24T17:37:01+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-29 09:59:31"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11627"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"2888"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4101"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46068"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94387"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112339"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 35-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with intense left sided abdominal pain after falling over and striking her upper abdomen against a chair. Her blood pressure is 130/95 and pulse 100/min. She has some bruising immediately under the rib cage and lower abdominal tenderness. The patient has no menstrual irregularities and uses the oral contraceptive pill.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine B-hCG is negative. An ultrasound of the abdomen and pelvis shows multiloculated mass with the largest diameter being 11cm on both ovaries with prominent vascularity. There is also presence of abdominal free fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate further management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound follow-up in 2 months","Ca-125 level","Percutaneous aspiration of the cyst","Laparoscopic cystectomy","Laparotomy and excision of the cyst"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of \u003Cstrong\u003Eovarian cyst rupture. \u003C/strong\u003EIn stable patients, simple ovarian cyst often resolve spontaneously and require no active intervention. However in this case, the patient\u0027s ultrasound demonstrates an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincidental finding of complex ovarian cysts\u003C/strong\u003E and further investigation is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the International Ovarian Tumor Analysis (IOTA) Group, characteristics of a malignant tumour on ultrasound are free intraperitoneal fluid, neovascularity, irregular multilocular solid mass, and a mass diameter of \u0026gt;10cm. \u003Cstrong\u003ECA-125\u003C/strong\u003E marker is then indicated in patients whose ultrasound finding raises suspicion of a malignancy to determine the Risk of Malignancy Index (RMI) score. A CA-125 measurement would not be indicated in a pre-menopausal women with an ultrasound showing no suspicious features. However, the patient described in this scenario does have potentially malignant features on her ultrasound - the size of the cyst and the prominent vascularity. Hence, measuring Ca-125 would be the appropriate next-step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk of Malignancy Index (RMI) score \u003C/strong\u003Eis scoring system that is widely used for risk assessment of ovarian tumour. It utilises ultrasound findings, CA-125 marker and the patient\u0027s menopausal status. In this case patient\u0027s RMI score should be determined with a referral to a gynaecologist or gynaecologic oncologist if the RMI is greater than 200.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound follow up\u003C/strong\u003E in two months is not the appropriate management plan in this case due to the sinister imaging finding. A more active intervention is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf an abdominal cystic lesion is thought to have malignant potential, \u003Cstrong\u003Easpiration\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided because of the risk of spillage of malignant cells. Cyst aspiration also possess risk of damaging nearby blood vessels and structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to measure CA-125 marker to calculate the RMI score prior to any surgical intervention. \u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic surgery\u003C/strong\u003E is preferred to laparotomy and excision of the cyst as laparoscopic surgery has been shown to be affiliated with fewer post-operative complications, shorter recovery time and hospital stay.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["RMI utilises ultrasound findings, CA-125 marker and patients\u0027 menopausal status to determine the risk of ovarian malignancy"],"references":["RCOG (2011). Green Top Guideline No. 62. Management of Suspected Ovarian Masses in Premenopausal Women. https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/gtg_62.pdf. Accessed 15/3/2022","Farghaly SA. Current diagnosis and management of ovarian cysts. Clin Exp Obstet Gynecol. 2014;41(6):609-12. PMID: 25551948.","Bottomley C, Bourne T. Diagnosis and management of ovarian cyst accidents.\u00a0Best Pract Res Clin Obstet Gynaecol. 2009;23(5):711-724. doi:10.1016/j.bpobgyn.2009; 23:711-24.","Yeoh M. Investigation and management of an ovarian mass. Australian Family Physician. 2015 Jan;44(1/2):48-52. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/january-february/investigation-and-management-of-an-ovarian-mass"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11627"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-30T08:50:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-30T08:51:04+09:30","number":10,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-08-30T08:50:41+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4254-10.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T030250Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=acdf605b05d13b418e750bec8f5dead4f657fd8003dbbd027fb4edaad5675f9b"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4254"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112339"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"2888"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici